{
  "text": "Synthesis of NAG can also be catalyzed by other proteins including argO encoded NAGS (O-NAGS) first identified in Campylobacter jejuni, S-NAGS, a short version of NAGS first identified in M. tuberculosis [CITATION_1] , and argH fused NAGS (H-NAGS) [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . O-NAGS has only 146 amino acids [CITATION_4] and although its sequence is related to the GNAT family, it does not have significant similarity to the NAT domain of the typical NAGS. S-NAGS is able to catalyze the formation of NAG, but has an extremely high Km for glutamate [CITATION_5] . H-NAGS, which includes a short version of NAGS fused to the C-terminus of argininosuccinate lyase (argH), has been found in some bacteria in the Alteromonas-Vibro group and is able to complement an argA E. coli mutant [CITATION_6] . These enzymes have been reviewed in detail by Xu et al. [CITATION_7] . More recently, a novel type of NAGS, the sequence of which is not related to any known NAGS, was identified in Corynebacterium glutamicum [CITATION_8] . The variety of these enzymes raised the question of how and why proteins with such high divergence have the ability to catalyze the formation of the same compound, NAG.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "9900466",
